<p class="csshide">&nbsp;</p>		<div class="item2"  id="newsblock27283">		
			<div class="newstitle1">
				<span id="star_27283">
									</span>
				<a href="/story/27283/Haiku_s_package_management_the_return_of_the_hybrid">Haiku's package management: the return of the hybrid</a>
			</div>
			
			<div class="newssubheader1">
			Linked by <a href="/editor/11">Thom Holwerda</a>			on Thu 22nd Aug 2013 21:00 UTC			</div>
			
			<div class="newscontent1">
				<a href="/topics/20"><img src="http://www.osnews.com/images/icons/20.gif" alt="BeOS &amp; Derivatives" class="timg" align="left" title="BeOS &amp; Derivatives" /></a>
			<div class="cquote"><p>Although I have been a lazy blogger lately we haven't been lazy working on our remaining tasks at all. So, unsurprisingly, since my previous post we have reached and passed a few nice milestones. The latest one is that we're finally able to build the gcc2/gcc4 hybrid Haiku images again, including all the software needed for the official release.
</p><p>
While that in itself isn't a particularly impressive feat - after all we were already able to build the complete gcc 2 part before - the interesting aspect is <a href="http://www.haiku-os.org/blog/bonefish/2013-08-12_package_management_return_hybrid">how we are doing it</a>.</p></div>
<p>
Interesting progress for Haiku.</p></div>
